			<div class="postrow">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Apple Guilty of E-Book Price Fixing
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1787116">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Alikat Astrae</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1787028#post1787028" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">Wow, eBooks are way too expensive.  They  cost more than actual paperbacks!  My guess would be that this is like  online music sales, where the industry has not yet caught up to  technological reality with regards to pricing structures, so they've  constructed a system that encourages piracy.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>See my many rants on publishers for my thoughts on this.  <br />
<br />
The blame really lies with the authors though for not self-publishing.  <br />
<br />
I realize why they still do not generally, but it frustrates me all the same (that is why I asked if you did Alikat).  <br />
<br />
The publishers are so exposed to being removed from the feedback loop, yet progress is slow in dethroning them entirely.<br />
<br />
They  are the worst when it comes to destroying culture and crippling signal;  as an example, it costs money to read a copy of the official ISO  standard on C++11, a situation which is competitive for most idiotic  event personally witnessed.<br />
<br />
As an aside, I would like to point  out that the official standard is often shorter and less numerous than  the multitude of books published on C++11 or other C++ standards and of  higher quality; feel free to draw any conclusions about what they  implies about the myriad of published books on the topic.<br />
<br />
Anyways,  back to the main topic: I am for anything that results in encumbered  publishing houses or other gate keepers dying a quicker death, an aim  which does not necessarily entail charging for the information no longer  being possible or common.<br />
<br />
Does no one else find it completely absurd that it is considered more favorable for information to no longer be available due to going out of print than it is for someone who does not own the copyright to archive that in some manner?<br />
<br />
That scenario feels incredibly short sighted and unethical to me; literally no one, not even the original author(s), is allowed to preserve that knowledge in that case if the publishers solely own the copyright.<br />
<br />
I cannot see even Adam Smith agreeing that is a good outcome for anyone.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="cleardiv"></div>
		</div>
	</div>
