			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Apple Guilty of E-Book Price Fixing
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1787263">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>MI Redeux</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1787116#post1787116" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">The blame really lies with the authors though for not self-publishing.  </div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>I don't know that I'd go so far as to say the blame lies on the AUTHORS, but I know I'm FAR more likely to buy an e-book on my extremely limited budget if they go the &quot;Steam Indie Games&quot; route and assume that lower prices mean more sales for them.<br />
<br />
Anthony Ryan is proving to be one of my favorite indie authors lately. I have three books of his &quot;Slab City&quot; series (only read the third one so far, excellent stuff, didn't know about the others until a few days ago) and one of his &quot;Raven's Shadow&quot; series (and am eagerly awaiting the second).<br />
<br />
I actually found out about him from a post by Dmitry in the &quot;What are you reading?&quot; thread, which mentioned &quot;Blood Song&quot;, and upon getting a few pages into it, I immediately bought the cheaper &quot;Slab City Blues: A Hymn to Gods Long Dead&quot; which proved to be a very pleasant futuristic noir novel.<br />
<br />
As a result of finding his stuff, I discovered that he published his first two novels in the Slab series for free. As a result of that, I discovered smashwords, which I have the distinct feeling I'll be utilizing in the near future when I'm in the mood for more science fiction or fantasy but don't feel like carrying paper books around. (I *despise* getting questioned about what I'm reading when people can see covers and spines during my lunch hour at work)
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
